London's response "addresses some of the core issues and it dismisses some  of the other questions," Adams said.
"But leaving that aside, the fact that the British government was moved to  make the response is very significant in itself," he said.
The meeting between Reynolds and Major Thursday was billed as an  "informal" sessions to allow the two leaders to assess their respective  efforts towards setting up a viable platform, by the summer, for a resumption  in the multiparty talks.
British troops were deployed in Northern Ireland in 1969, and the province  has been directly administered by London since 1972.
More than 3,000 people have lost their lives in the sectarian violence  that has plagued Northern Ireland for more than a quarter of a century.
The IRA has fought to end British presence in Northern Ireland while  Protestant loyalists want the province to remain under British rule.
